snippet.textDisplay:
Touch dirty box with hands ... hands are now dirty. Pull out bag with dirty hands ... bag is now dirty. Put dirty bag on clean side. Same with medicine bottle, etc.


Suggestion: remove bag from box, medicine from bag, etc. with tongs, shelf reacher, etc. Make sure that the business end of the tongs remain clean.

snippet.textDisplay: Though I would do a few things differently this is so far the most logical video I've seen with regards to groceries. I always use two wipes one for each hand and that way I don't touch the item with a dirty hand as Im moving it around. I use presoaked wipes so I don't have to keep handling the spray bottle with dirty hands, then the bottle becomes one more thing to wipe in the end. Also with the cereal, if the box has a very shiny coating, I wipe it, if I remove the inner bag i don't touch it, just dump it as I don't consider my hand clean during this process. Im sure you did this but after its all done, the "dirty" counter gets cleaned very well. I have always done my groceries this way as I have Lupus and can not have germs in my environment. I also treat  take out food this way however now I will not be getting any as its an extra risk I just don't need. Thank you Dr Jeff! You are spot on and so amazing to see a Dr who actually understands the chain of asepsis. For this virus to get under control, every Dr would need to be like you. Unfortunately thats not the case. Stay safe and healthy!

snippet.textDisplay: I am a home health nurse. I have a question. I had seen somewhere to wash the bags you bring in (the fabric ones) but disinfect the bottom of them before sitting them down. We have been given the "surgical" masks and gloves and hand sanitizer but can the Covic 19 virus get through these? I had a biologist say it can. Would you please answer for me? I am trying to keep my patients safe as well as myself. Thank you for all that you do! Also, another question. Disposal of briefs that have been "soiled"; I have been putting in plastic bags and putting into another brash bag that is tied closed separate from the other trash. I'm taking proper precautions but is there any other tips you can tell me? Thank you for your service and prayers for you and everyone who is in healthcare fighting this virus. God bless you! You are appreciated! We have lost patients due to them not wanting us to come into their home even though we have PPE equipment. So far I still have a job but not sure how much longer with the difference of things being reported in the media. If I get laid off I will go to a hospital or a nursing home.

snippet.textDisplay:
Thank you for introducing us to some safer practices!
I'm going to mix up a recommended bleach solution to wipe off all solid surfaces of food containers I bring in, and let them air dry. With a batch made fresh, a dip of my rag each time refreshes the solution with which I'll be wiping items. I'll wear gloves for this to protect my hands, and wash them thoroughly afterward as well.
cdc.gov/disasters/bleach.html
I was a former girl scout leader and dipping plates and utensils and letting them air dry (via dipping bags) was the final step in the washing process, so this idea resonates with me. Just measure the bleach to keep proportions correct. It doesn't take much.
I've been a long time washer of veggies I will chop, but hadn't thought about those I'll peel, too.
Great suggestions, Dr., thank you!
